"&#xa0;\nWritten evidence from the National Council for Voluntary Organisations &#xa0;Crime Reduction Policies: a co-ordinated approach?Summary&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nInvestment and spend on rehabilitation services&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;The impact the PbR model has on the way providers work with service users:&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;The impact of PbR on the voluntary sector. &#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;Market stewardship proposals and supply chain standards&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;November 2013\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n BWB and NCVO, \nOctober \n2013. \nPayment by results contracts: a legal analysis of terms and process\n. \nAvailable at:\n \nhttp://www.ncvo-vol.org.uk/pbr\n NCVO, June 2013. \nNCVO response to the MoJ’s proposed payment mechanism for the Rehabilitation programme.\n Available at: \nhttp://blogs.ncvo.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/ruth-bridenbach-roe/NCVO-feedback-to-MOJ-payment-mechanism.pdf\n \n BWB and NCVO, October 2013. \nPayment by results contracts: a legal analysis of terms and process. \nAvailable at:\n \nhttp://www.ncvo-vol.org.uk/pbr\n \nNCVO’s survey of WP subcontractors found that 13 out of 98 have had to ‘park’ customers because the cost of the intervention exceeds the payment. The same research showed that \n29 out of 98 respondents believed that prime contractors were inappropriately withholding clients (“creaming”).\nNCVO, September 2012. \nPerceptions and experiences of the voluntary sector. \nAvailable at:\nhttp://www.ncvo.org.uk/images/documents/practical_support/public_services/SIG%20survey%202012%20report.pdf\n \n NCVO, June 2013. \nNCVO response to the MoJ’s proposed payment mechanism for the\n Rehabilitation programme.\n Available at: \nhttp://blogs.ncvo.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/ruth-bridenbach-roe/NCVO-feedback-to-MOJ-payment-me\nchanism.pdf\n MoJ, June 2013. \nPayment Mechanism: Straw Man. \nAvailable at: \nhttp://www.justice.gov.uk/downloads/rehab-prog/payment-mechanism.pdf\n \n MoJ, October 2013. \nTransforming Rehabilitation Programme- Payment Mechanism: Market feedback and development considerations. \nAvailable at: \nhttp://www.justice.gov.uk/downloa\nds/rehab-prog/competition/payment-mechanism-feedback.pdf\n NCVO, June 2013. \nNCVO response to the MoJ’s proposed payment mechanism for the Rehabilitation programme.\n Available at: \nhttp://blogs.ncvo.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/ruth-bridenbach-roe/NCVO-feedback-to-MOJ-payment-mechanism.pdf\n \nMoJ, October 2013. \nTransforming Rehabilitation Programme- Payment Mechanism: Market feedback and de\nvelopment considerations. \nAvailable at: \nhttp://www.justice.gov.uk/downloads/rehab-prog/competition/payment-mechanism-feedback.pdf\n, p. 4\n \nThis has bee\nn a common finding of our recent analysis of PbR contracts. \nBWB and NCVO, October 2013. \nPayment by results contracts: a legal analysis of terms and process. \nAvailable at:\n \nhttp://www.ncvo-vol.org.uk/pbr\n, p. 22\n BWB and NCVO, 2013. \nPayment by results contracts: a legal analysis of terms and process \nhttp://www.ncvo-vol.org.uk/pbr\n, p. 8\n, p. 25\n \nNCVO, September 2012. \nPerceptions and experiences of the voluntary sector\n. \nAvailable at:\nhttp://www.ncvo.org.uk/images/documents/practical_support/public_services/SIG%20survey%202012%20report.pdf\n The surv\ney also found that 87 and 82 percent of voluntary sector and local authority respondents respectively do not believe that PbR contracts will improve service quality. \nCompact Voice, 2013.  \nhttp://www.compactvoice.org.uk/blogs/compact-voice/2013/08/13/local-compact-survey-results-2013-payment-results\n For the smallest contract, Norfolk and Suffolk, providers will still need to demo\nnstrate access to at least £5.25 million (approximately half of the contract\n’\ns total value).\n \nBWB and NCVO, 2013. \nPayment by results contracts: a legal analysis of terms and process \nhttp://www.ncvo-vol.org.uk/pbr\n, \np. 14\n A list of the MoJ’s 5 key Market Stewardship principles, including that all organisations but adhere to the principles of the Compact, is available in the ‘Principles of Competition’ document. \nMoJ, September 2013\n. \nPrinciples of Competition. \nAvailable at: \nhttp://www.justice.gov.uk/downloads/rehab-prog/competition/moj-principles-of-competition.pdf\n, p. 6\n \nMoJ\n, October 2013. \nTransforming Rehabilitation Programme- Payment Mechanism: Market feedback and development considerations. \nAvailable at: \nhttp://www.justic\ne.gov.uk/downloads/rehab-prog/competition/payment-mechanism-feedback.pdf\n, p. 6\n NCVO is currently contributing to DWP’s review of the Merlin Standard through the Merlin Advisory Board, and is a member of the DWP’s Best Practice Group on the Work Programme\n"